results.notes:
The color of the disc for these two specimens varies between very dark gray to brownish-olivaceous gray. This coincides with the variations of disc color observed on other examples of what I have believed to be A. rooseveltensis. The seventh photo best shows the cap colors for these specimens.

Other traits seen in these photos match the currently held concept of rooseveltensis, including: stipe with small white floccose scales that are easily wiped off, striations occupying ~50% of the radius of the cap, cap color gray along (at least) the outer 50%, volva fairly thick and buried in the soil, upon extraction from the soil volva detaching from the stipe base and breaking into pieces large enough to easily collect.

Habitat associated with rooseveltensis is lawns near oak and/or hickory. These two specimens were found on a lawn near a large hickory tree. (No oak nearby.) The in-situ photos show them exactly as they appeared; the fruit bodies were not posed.

A key rooseveltensis feature is spore morphology. This material was scoped and the spores observed were mainly broadly ellipsoid with some ellipsoid and a few subglobose. This matches the currently held concept of rooseveltensis.

results.notes: Green gills had a blue-green appearance to the natural eyes in the field, then appeared more swampy green later on. Blue to blue-green hues were evident, similar to Psilocybe cyanescens bluing, on the pileus margins, but not as a result of bruising, handling, or gaseous exposure. Spore prints failed due to either insect larvae or deliquescence, but during the process, the prints appeared black – yes, black. Aroma was strong and not bakery like such as observed with Inocybe calamistrata, nor was it like cucumbers as observed with Psilocybe caerulescens. I cannot describe the aroma, but would call it neutral and neither pleasant or unpleasant. In the field, I was thinking “Lepiota” or “Leucolepiota.” After an hour of watching them spore print, I thought, “Almost definitely Inocybe.” Now, I leave it up to the Mushroom Observer mycologists and mushroomists.

Cap/stipe flesh white overall, staining pinkish, then grey, then nearly black (sorry no photos of this).
Young pores white. Mature pores still quite white, going buff, except where stained.
Pores staining pinkish, slowly to nearly black.
Taste: mild.
Odor: not distinctive.
Flesh quite firm, even on the big ones.

Distinctly ribbed/reticulate over more than half the stipe, more so on bigger ones.

As I see it, this screams “T. Alboater,” but I have not been able to find any observations/descriptions of such with this level of reticulation. Whether this is even real “reticulation” is not clear to me either. Does any one else find Alboater with a stipe this clearly not smooth?
